manufacturerProductDescription.media_text: About Us GIGABYTE offers a comprehensive product lineup that aims to “Upgrade Your Life.” With expertise encompassing consumer, business, gaming, and cloud systems, GIGABYTE established its reputation as one of the leaders in the industry with products including motherboards, graphics cards, laptops, mini PCs, monitors, and other PC components and accessories. reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on August 6, 2022
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Unbelievable value with some caveats
reviews.reviewText: Pros:- Awesome value; a $170 itx mobo with Wifi6, ddr5 support sounds too good to be true; but this is the real deal.- Feels heavy and solid with very little flex. All headers and connectors are very sturdily attachedCons:As another review mentioned, these boards were originally the Z690I Ultra, but there was a defect in the PCIe expansion slot, so the board is only capable of PCIe3x16. This is not a big deal in 2022 as the highest end graphics cards still do not utilize all of PCIe 3 x16’s bandwidth.Weird header placement. This is my only major gripe with this board. The front audio panel header is hidden in a crevice behind a heatsink, that’s inaccessible on the CPU cooler is installed. I didn’t realize this until it was too late, and ended up having to uninstall my CPU cooler, pull up the daughter board pull out the audio cable.There are several other headers (sys fan and rgb) in a tiny crevice in between the GPU and a heatsink. You won’t be able to reach those once the GPU is installed. So if you wanna install a second fan in your chassis, you’ll have to uninstall the GPU first.The CPU power header is in an extremely hard to get to corner (nr200 chassis) it might be easier to attach the CPU power cable first before installing the board.Overall though, the negatives are nothing a little time, patience and due diligence can’t solve. The feature and price to feature ratio far outweigh the cons. Do a little bit of planning before starting a build with this beauty and you’ll be fine!

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on August 6, 2022
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars is ITX and pcie 3.0
reviews.reviewText: it fits it is Z690i so next gen compatible we hope (Intel is saying it will be )and ddr 5 not DDR 4 and for a decent priceonly thing people may not know is it is PCIe 3.0 16 GPU slot that is the lite in its name ....but even a 3090 can not saturate a PCIe 3.0 at this time so for me not worth buying same board for twice the $ but the NVME M.2 slots are both PCIe 4.0 speed so plenty fast storage .....in my opinion you can not go wrong with this board if doing a Intel build right now and need ITX platform ,.best bang for the $ I could find at the time I was searching

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on February 10, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 1.0 out of 5 stars QFlash+ Is An Absolute Joke
reviews.reviewText: Received an early build that didn’t support my 13th gen Core CPU. No worries though, because I should be able to QFlash+ the BIOS to update to a revision with gen 13 support. No CPU required! Cool! But wait…. You must have a flash drive. Smaller than 32GB. Formatted to FAT32. MUST BE USB 2.0.I cannot tell you how insanely difficult it was to make sure the 3 requirements were met. It’s 2023, flash drives have been USB 3.0 for over 7 years. They are all pretty much over 32GB. And Windows 10 doesn’t let you natively format to FAT32. After spending over an hour trying to find a USB 2.0 flash drive for purchase nearby + 1 hour tearing my house apart I managed to find a literal 12 year old flash drive in an old backpack. Long since forgotten.Then, I followed Gigabyte’s lousy instructions that leave too much room for interpretation. I consulted numerous videos and Reddit posts trying to figure out what I was doing wrong. Nothing. I tried every BIOS revision, every possible permutation of the flagging process. Nothing worked. It’s now 2am and I have to cut my losses and wait the week for another motherboard to arrive. It definitely won’t be a lousy Gigabyte. I honestly don’t know if I’ll ever use their stuff again at this point.To make matters even worse, I bought a used version that was missing parts, screws, and had an old cooler brace still screwed on under the CPU socket. It never should have been resold!

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on November 10, 2022
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars MAKE NOTE OF THIS
reviews.reviewText: It comes without internet drivers so you cant install windows (no internet) that you need to be able to update drivers. BUT you can press shift+F10 and enter “OOBE\BYPASSNRO” into the command prompt to bypass installing windows without internet and then the drivers will auto update.You’re welcome.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on March 29, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 4.0 out of 5 stars Great value, but wish I knew before buying...
reviews.reviewText: That the itx form factor has changed in the past 3 years. Every 3-5 years, I build or upgrade my PC setups, and the last itx case was extremely tight, but I was able to fit in a low profile cooler at least. With this mobo, it's a requirement to do water cooling, which I was planning on doing anyways. The thing is, it took me 3 tries to do it because the clearance is so tight and my cooler had to be rotated twice to get the setup to the point where the water tubes were not being pushed down against the fan.The 2nd worst thing is DDR5 support. As of early 2023, DDR4 is still a much better value than DDR5, about 1/2 the price and probably 90% of the performance. Unfortunately itx DDR4 boards with 1700 socket were not very common to find.All of the other connections are extremely tight. For example, the front HD Audio connector is initially lodged under the m2 expansion pcb. You have to unscrew the layered heatsink and then pull out the m.2 expansion pcb. Speaking of which, the mobo supports 2 m.2 drives, but only one works. I only need one, but having one not work is a real bummer. Lastly, the usb-a connector to the mobo isn't working, but I haven't figured out if this is the case connector or mobo issue.It works, and it was $20 cheaper than the competition, but I ended up spending $60 more on RAM and could have potentially saved more on cooling, and still my new setup is lacking front USB and m.2 expansion. So it's bittersweet.

reviews.reviewTitle: 1.0 out of 5 stars Did not have PCI 5..
reviews.reviewText: Did not have PCI 5, theres a bunch of connectors and cables that were included but didnt really need to be connected or something. worked in a dan h20 case.

reviews.reviewTitle: Gigabyte should recall this system board!
reviews.reviewText: Gigabyte should recall this system board! PCI Express root nub is generation 20000+ warning in Windows Envet Viewer in 3 minutes. Using the same CPU, memory, SSD and graphics card on MSI Z790 motherboard, then everything works fine. I'm also very disappointed with Amazon Canada...I should be able to return the board and get a refund. Instead, I paid $350 for an MSI Z790 to prove that the Gigabyte Z690 was faulty.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United Kingdom on March 13, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: A great small form factor motherboard
reviews.reviewText: I got this to upgrade the PC connected to my TV. (it was running on a second generation core i5, so it really was overdue!).The installation was a breeze - apart from some initial confusion on my part as to how to connect up the front panel sound connection (it's hidden and needs a bit of disassembly to reveal it - easy once I had worked out the issue!).It's all working really well with DDR5 RAM and a Core i5 12600 processor. I'm using the integrated graphics which has been fine for my needs (so far...).Just one thing to note, you really will need to use the intel cooling fan. I tried another (always liked Arctic, but couldn't get a fit for this one!).

reviews.reviewTitle: Great value board. Would buy again
reviews.reviewText: My first ITX build and had no issues with this board. Need to update bios firmware for the 13th Intel gen cpu but that's normal on all boards. Was able to fit cpu frame + Arctic freezer 280 AIO with some modification to the mounting brackets. The ends of the brackets need to be cut back about 2mm off each end, the pump head plastic cover needed to be removed and 3mm shaved off the end with the pump fan. All fit snug into CoolerMaster NR200 case. Be aware if it matters that the ultra lite model board has pcie3 interface for gpu. Best value board.

I read some reviews before purchasing this model and they were mixed. Unfortunately I took my chances with it and it turned out to be complete garbage as a lot of people said. Sent it back and been waiting for over a month for a refund. Don't recommend :(
